social_posts.post_text:
We were changed forever the day my husband died. Now, almost 2.5 years later, we’ve settled into our new normal. It’s still hard, there are reminders everywhere of the hole in our lives, and my grief over what my kids lost weighs HEAVY. But at the end of the day, I’m so freakin proud of us. ❤️

We know where we want our relationship to go, but the when and the how is unknown. And that’s what you learn, after loss or divorce in your 30’s/40’s. That you have to live in the moment and enjoy the happiness you have RIGHT NOW. Stay present. Trust that even though life isn’t all figured out, we are right here for a reason. ❤️

 When you’re in your 20’s and in a relationship, you feel like you’re on a timeline - engaged, wedding, house, kids. When I first knew I could have something serious with Pony, I wanted to nail down our timeline. But with long distance and 5 kids, there can’t be a rush. So we live here, in the present. And it’s a pretty special place to be! ❤️

Awkwaaaaard 😬

Thankfully, in my small town most people know my story. But when I DO meet someone new, it can be awkward.  2+ years later and I still don’t know if that question will bring tears to my eyes, cause me to have a breakdown, or make me be very blunt ( “he’s dead” vs “he passed away” ). Wild life, as a widow. ❤️

SNOW much fun with my sissy today….shreddin’ & dodgin’ 75 kids on a field trip 😂🎿🐰

Grand Cayman latergram…❤️

Highly recommend!! Grand Cayman was absolutely gorgeous, weather was hot and sunny every day, and the Rum Point area was quiet and full of nature. We all loved to be able to kayak out in front of our house to swim with stingrays and take walks to see starfish, crabs, fish, etc. 

Family, experiences, and making memories mean everything to us. I love to see these 6 cousins grow up together! Life hasn’t always been easy (duh)….but we all work hard to play hard. ❤️

You may THINK you know how you’d react if your spouse died, how you would grieve….but you’d probably be wrong. Destructive behaviors are 💯 a part of grieving for most of us….and sadly, we usually end up feeling guilty, judged, and alone. It sucks, but I’m so thankful for my widow friends and community. I’m going to miss my Monday nights playing volleyball and laughing with these amazing mamas + my sissy! 🏐 ❤️🔥

18 (+ 1 in the belly!) kids between us but we found some much needed time for ourselves! And turns out, we still kinda got it! 😂🙌😜

Matt was the most amazing, selfless father and husband. If there was an opportunity to be involved with the kids, he was the first one to sign up. Every night he’d come home from work, change his clothes, eat dinner, and take over with the kids. Nightly baths and reading were his thing and more often than not, he’d fall asleep laying next to one of them. I wish, more than anything, that he could be here to see these kids grow up. I hate, hate, HATE that they have to have such a large hole in their lives. But at the same time, I’m so freakin thankful that he AND they had such a strong bond. We have so many pictures, videos, and memories of EXPERIENCES together - whether it was coaching soccer, traveling, or taking the kids mini golfing. We were so lucky. ❤️

Happy birthday up there, Matt….it’s so fun getting older, while you get to stay the same age. 😜 ❤️ 😇
Spring Break mood 😂🤷‍♀️🏝️ 🌊❤️

It only takes one life changing moment to discover how precious life is, how short our time is with our kids and the ones we love. 💔

We are all aware of this & yet the majority of us feel completely exempt from the worst of it.  I know I felt that way. 

So let this be your encouragement to take the trip (big OR small - enjoy experiences with your kids!), get in the pictures, record the videos, get on the boogie board and get dirty in the sand! 🌊 

Because at the end of the day….whether it’s next week or 30 years from now, these memories you’re making and documenting will be what your family holds on to. 💕

A fun weekend with some St Louis lunatics and a cute baby! ❤️🍻 ⚾️

Father’s Day. It never gets easier. I hate that my kids don’t get this amazing dad in their lives. It will never seem fair, or make sense to me. 💔

I’m so grateful I got to witness him be such a great, hands on dad for 9 years. ❤️

I’m so grateful for all the memories we made. We valued experiences so much and documented it all….which is now what we hold on to as time goes on. ❤️

I’m grateful to the men that have stepped up to fill some of the voids, loving on my kiddos (especially Jack!)! It means the world to me. 😊

3 years without him. THREE YEARS. 💔 

I had a good friend say to me the other day “I didn’t know Matt, but from what you’ve shared your son is a lot like him!” 

And that was WILD. That I can have good friends in my life that didn’t know this amazing man, husband, and father. That only get to know him through my picture and stories. 

That only know ME as a widow. 😳

So please, keep asking about him and talking about him with us. I promise you - we love it! Because he is so missed. ❤️

@museumoficecream was a hit in Chicago! 🍦 

A few tips…
1️⃣ Buy tickets in advance! The price fluctuates based on how busy they get, and it can get expensive. Plus, less busy = better experience in the sprinkle pool! 👏 
2️⃣ Enjoy the free ice cream vs buying it. We got a Dove bar at the beginning, and 3 different & unique (hot dog flavored?!!) icecream treats along the way. 
3️⃣ Really explore and enjoy each room. There are lots of little things to do! 
4️⃣ Best for younger kids. My 12 yr old was into about half of the activities. 😂
5️⃣ It’s worth it for the sprinkle pool. Kids LOVED that! But it’s also like a playground where parents sit and let their kids go wild. 😉

Seattle/Alaska blended family vaca photo dump 🚢 🏔️ ☀️ 

The cruise to Alaska was breathtakingly gorgeous! The sea plane tour was definitely a highlight and worth the money - what an experience we will all remember forever, including Jason getting to sit copilot! 

We did lots of hiking/exploring and saw bald eagles, salmon, a sea lion, and pods of whales from our balcony. The mountains and views every day were seriously so gorgeous. Pictures don’t begin to do it justice! 

We were on one of Royal Caribbean’s smaller ships in two balcony rooms. I forgot how small cruise ship rooms are! 🤪 But there was a lot to do on the ship for the kids with indoor and outdoor pools, arcade, air hockey, bingo, random shows/trivia, rock climbing, indoor skydiving, boogie boarding and unlimited ice cream…..which meant I made us all walk up 8 flights of stairs multiple times a day which also meant they sometimes hated me. 😂🤷‍♀️

Food was good and what you’d expect for an all inclusive. We sat down for 3 long formal dinners, which definitely had their “shit show” moments….but they were also my favorite times to talk and laugh with the kids. The buffet had a ton of choices and we all officially need a sugar detox! 

We felt safe leaving the kids in the rooms at night while Jason and I gambled or did some much needed alone time bar hopping! 👏👏👏

It was nice to finish our trip seeing my Seattle family and going Museum of Flight. 

There were moments of sibling fights, stress, and all the other hard stuff you expect when you are blending families for 10 days…..but seeing these kids laugh, adventure, and make memories with us was worth it! ❤️

Also, thanks to @nkammeraad_kttwtravel for helping us plan yet another trip! If ya need an expert on Disney/Universal, cruises, all inclusives….she’s your girl. Where are we going next?!
